200 NPS responses is a gift — but it's also a trap if we treat the score as the answer. NPS tells us how people feel. It rarely tells us why in enough fidelity to redesign anything. Let's slow down before we act on it.

A few things I'd want to know before recommending a next move:

Have the comments been read — or just counted? 200 responses with even short verbatims is a goldmine. Has anyone done qualitative coding on them yet? Often the score distribution is misleading and the language patterns in the comments are where the real insight lives.
What part of "onboarding" are detractors actually pointing at? Onboarding is a journey — signup, first login, first value moment, first invite-a-teammate, first "aha". Detractors often cluster around one specific cliff. Without segmenting, "fix onboarding" is too big to act on.
Who are the detractors? Role? Company size? Use case? Self-serve vs sales-led? A 6/10 from a power user means something completely different than a 6/10 from someone who never made it past step 2.
When did they answer? NPS captured 2 days into onboarding tells a different story than NPS captured 30 days in. Recall decay is real — the further from the moment, the more rationalized the feedback.
What's missing from NPS that we'd need to actually fix this? NPS is self-report after the fact. It can't tell us: where they dropped off, what they tried before quitting, what they expected, what their face looked like when the modal appeared. We'll need behavioral + observational data alongside it.
